<taxonomicName id="F91BDAE3325A6862A369EF07D7604F60" authority="Day, 1953" authorityName="Day" authorityYear="1953" class="Polychaeta" family="Syllidae" genus="Sphaerosyllis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sphaerosyllis capensis" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="capensis">Sphaerosyllis capensis Day, 1953</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2E2F5D2E8534760088F77CEB17B93983" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" type="notes">
<paragraph id="0D514AB2FBBB23A5EC227BF12A70CEFF" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F351FDFCFF9151207720423AA530D066" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997">
Questionable status. Reported from Greece by 
<bibRefCitation id="9CFFD4E4D71C784C18C99F72D577E4EB" author="Arvanitidis, Christos" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of Marine Science" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" pagination="73 - 96" title="Polychaete fauna of the Aegean Sea: inventory and new information" volume="66" year="2000">Arvanitidis (2000a)</bibRefCitation>
, in the Mediterranean also reported from Spain (
<bibRefCitation id="C4D38113E974BBAA7C3C18BE92552C52" author="San Martin, G" journalOrPublisher="Actas II Simposio Iberico de Estudios del Bentos Marino" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" pagination="171 - 182" title="Una coleccion de anelidos poliquetos de las costas mediterraneas andaluzas." volume="3" year="1981">
San 
<normalizedToken id="3E0CED635827AC4DDC760355253D9ADA" originalValue="MartÃ­n">Martin</normalizedToken>
et al. 1981b
</bibRefCitation>
), otherwise distributed along the coast of South Africa and in the Indian Ocean. The specimens may have been confused with other Mediterranean species. 
<taxonomicName id="4659B5C64C268300314364FEE4CBC8B5" class="Polychaeta" family="Syllidae" genus="Sphaerosyllis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sphaerosyllis capensis" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="capensis">Sphaerosyllis capensis</taxonomicName>
is distinguished from many congeners by having all antennae in line. However, the position of the antennae in preserved material may be misleading if fixation has caused muscle contraction (
<bibRefCitation id="61FC000E83EBE9D925A792FFD6ABBAC1" author="Riser, Nathan W" journalOrPublisher="Ophelia" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" pagination="209 - 218" title="An evaluation of taxonomic characters in the genus Sphaerosyllis (Polychaeta: Syllidae)" volume="Supplement 5" year="1991">Riser 1991</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
